, (388287, 'To speculate without facts is to attempt to enter a house of which one has not the key, by wandering aimlessly round and round, searching the walls and now and then peeping through the windows. Facts are the key.', 29953, 0), (388288, 'Every day that we read the news we have the possibility of being confronted with a fact about our world that is wildly different from what we thought we knew.', 50466, 0), (388289, 'The true business of the philosopher, though not flattering to his vanity, is merely to ascertain, arrange and condense the facts.', 61359, 0), (388290, 'I have always loved to begin with the facts, to observe them, to walk in the light of experiment and demonstrate as much as possible, and to discuss the results.', 61360, 0), (388291, 'But what are facts, really, except things we’ve already proven? There could be lots of almost-facts out there, still waiting for proof.', 61361, 0), (388292, 'Facts are a strange thing . . . when you know the facts to be true, they turn you into a revolutionary.', 3938, 0), (388293, 'History is often made and buttressed by myths and folklore rather than facts.', 61362, 0), (388294, 'The fact was never give a chance to the possibility', 51181, 0), (388295, 'Cosmology is a science which has only a few observable facts to work with.', 61363, 0), (388296, 'Finding that no religion is based on facts and cannot therefore be true, I began to reflect what must be the condition of mankind trained from infancy to believe in errors.', 2727, 0), (388297, 'A law of nature is not a formula drawn up by a legislator, but a mere summary of the observed facts — a ''bundle of facts.'' Things do not act in a particular way because there is a law, but we state the ''law'' because they act in that way.', 30775, 0), (388298, 'Ive allways wondered what the 4 letters in the word LIFE stands for. I know understand that it stands for: Little Interesting Facts Everyday.', 8504, 0), (388299, 'I am concerned with facts of quite unverifiable 